# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: complete-game
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The **1904 major league baseball season** was contested from April 14 to October 10, 1904.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans and New York Giants finished atop the standings for the American League and National League, respectively.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason: with still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues, the Giants declined to meet the Americans in the 1904 World Series.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the Americans were the defending World Series from the 1903 season.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns and Detroit Tigers played 11 consecutive games against each other in September—the first six in Detroit and the final five in St.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis—the most games played consecutively between two teams in major league history.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings shortened their name to the Chicago White Sox.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The 1904 schedule consisted of 154 games (an increase from 140 from the previous season) for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 140-game, 20-games-each format that had been in place from the 1901 season.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American League would see their final day of the regular season on October 9 & 10, respectively.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the New York Highlanders, in a rescheduled game, to play at a ballpark in a different locality.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] 29 tie games (18 in AL, 11 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] With still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues regarding the staging of the World Series, the New York Giants refused to play against the Boston Americans or any other team from what they considered an inferior league.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators leave American League Park (where they played three seasons) and move into a new American League Park, where they would go on to play seven seasons through 1910.
[src:complete-game/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Highlanders play one game at Wiedenmeyer's Park in Newark, New Jersey on Sunday, July 17, as a makeup between them and the Detroit Tigers and to avoid New York City's blue laws.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The **1914 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1914, with the first game of the inaugural major league season of the Federal League (having previously existed as a minor league the year before).
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The league declared itself as a "third major league", with its own eight teams, in competition with the established National and American Leagues.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League regular season ended on October 6 with the Boston Braves as champions, and the American League regular season concluded the next day with the Philadelphia Athletics as champions.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League season ended on October 10, and saw the Indianapolis Hoosiers winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the National and American Leagues began with Game 1 of the 11th World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 4 on October 13.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Braves swept the Athletics in four games, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Both the National and American Leagues rejected offers by the Federal League for a postseason matchup.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1913 season.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each of the established National and American Leagues.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers renamed as the Brooklyn Robins.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The 1914 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format first put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Most teams played more than 154 games, due to tie games (called on account of darkness or weather) that had to be replayed; tie games are excluded from team standings, but the statistics of individual players are included in their season totals.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 13, with a game between Buffalo and Baltimore.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, and featured all 16 teams of those leagues, only the third time those two leagues started their season on the same day (the 1912 season had been the second).
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League had its final day of the regular season on October 6, while the American League's final day of the regular season was October 7.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series between AL and NL champions took place between October 9 and October 13.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 10.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] 43 tie games (18 in AL, 10 in NL, 15 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Braves sweeping the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1914 World Series in four games.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National and American Leagues refused a postseason against the Federal League.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Across two leagues, Dave Davenport tied as a leader in saves at 6 (2 with the Cincinnati Reds of the NL and 4 with the St.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Attendance data for Federal League teams is unavailable.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] They previously played their on August 1 and August 8.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] In all, 29 of their 79 home games were played at Fenway Park.
[src:complete-game/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The team would only play at Fenway through July of the following season.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The **1924 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1924.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the New York Giants and Washington Senators as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 21st World Series on October 4 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The Senators defeated the Giants, four games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1923 season.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The 1924 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 15, featured all sixteen teams, for the first time since 1922.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, while the American League would see its final day of the regular season the following day with a game between the Washington Senators and Boston Red Sox.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 4 and October 10.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (5 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:complete-game/1924-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 10 with the Washington Senators defeating the New York Giants in the 1924 World Series in seven games.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The **1934 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1934.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the St.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and Detroit Tigers as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 31st World Series on October 3 and ended with Game 7 on October 9.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals then defeated the Tigers, four games to three, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1931.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1933 season.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The second All-Star Game was held on July 10 at the Polo Grounds in New York, New York, home of the New York Giants.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The 1934 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 17, featured all sixteen teams, the first since the 1931 season.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 30, which also saw all sixteen teams play, continued the trend which began with the 1930 season.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second time that both Opening Day and the final day of the season saw all sixteen teams play, the previous being in 1931.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 3 and October 9.
[src:complete-game/1934-major-league-baseball-season] 8 tie games (5 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
