[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The **1964 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1964.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 4, with the St.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 61st World Series on October 7 and ended with Game 7 on October 15.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] In the fifth iteration of this World Series matchup, the Cardinals defeated the Yankees, four games to three, capturing their seventh championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1946.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] As of 2024, the Cardinals are the only National League team to have an edge over the Yankees in series played (3–2), despite holding a losing record in World Series games against them (13–15).
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Los Angeles Dodgers from the 1963 season.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The 35th All-Star Game was held on July 7 at Shea Stadium in New York, New York, home of the New York Mets.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] This season is often remembered for the end of the New York Yankees' third dynasty, as they won their 29th American League Championship in 44 seasons.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The 1964 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 10 teams.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other nine teams of their respective league.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American League since the 1961 season and by the National League since the 1962 season, and would be used until 1969.
