[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] CBS and NBC aired weekend *Game of the Week* broadcasts.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] By 1964, CBS paid $895,000 total for the rights to six teams, with the New York Yankees getting a $550,000 share.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The six clubs that exclusively played nationally televised games on NBC were paid $1.2 million total.
[src:complete-game/1964-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series aired on NBC.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] In baseball, a **complete game** (**CG**) is the act of a pitcher pitching an entire game without the benefit of a relief pitcher.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] A starting pitcher who is replaced by a pinch hitter in the final half inning of a game will still be credited with a complete game.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Complete games have become increasingly rare over the course of baseball history.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] In the early 20th century, pitchers completed almost all of the games they started, and they were generally expected to do so.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] In modern baseball, the feat is much more rare.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Since 1975, no pitcher has thrown 30 or more complete games in a season; in the 21st century, only twice has any pitcher thrown 10 or more complete games in a season.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] In the early 20th century, it was common for most good Major League Baseball (MLB) pitchers to pitch a complete game almost every start, barring injury or ejection.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Pitchers were expected to complete games they started.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Over the course of the 20th and 21st centuries, complete games became less common, to the point where a modern pitcher may pitch an entire season without throwing a complete game.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] (In the 2024 MLB season, 0.6% of starts were complete games.) To put this in perspective, as recently as the 1980s, 10–15 complete games a year by a star pitcher was not unheard of, and in 1980, Oakland Athletics pitcher Rick Langford threw 22 consecutive complete games.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Years earlier, Robin Roberts of the Philadelphia Phillies threw 28 consecutive complete games, spanning the 1952 and 1953 seasons.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] In 1962, a news article detailed Bo Belinsky's concern when he failed to complete six starts in a row.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] This change has been brought about by strict adherence to pitch counts as a basis for removing a pitcher, even though he may appear to be pitching well, and new pitching philosophies in general.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Many have come to believe that the risk of arm injuries becomes far more prevalent after a pitcher has thrown 100 to 120 pitches in a single game.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Though Hall-of-Famer Nolan Ryan once threw well over 200 pitches in a single game (a 1974 contest in which he pitched 13 innings), it is now rare for a manager to allow a pitcher to throw more than 120 pitches in a start.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Former pitcher Carl Erskine noted the increase in ex-pitchers on coaching staffs since the 1950s, whom he considered better evaluators of a pitchers' ability to pitch late into games.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Given this, sabermetricians generally regard Cy Young's total of 749 complete games as the career baseball record that will never be broken.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Further supporting the belief is that only three pitchers (Young, Ryan, and Don Sutton) even made at least 749 starts in their careers.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] James Shields threw 11 complete games in the 2011 season for the Tampa Bay Rays, becoming the first pitcher to reach double digits in a single season since CC Sabathia threw 10 complete games for the Cleveland Indians and Milwaukee Brewers in 2008.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] The last pitcher to throw as many as 15 complete games in a single season was Curt Schilling, who accomplished that feat for the Philadelphia Phillies in 1998.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] The last pitcher to throw 20 complete games in a single season was Fernando Valenzuela, who did so for the Los Angeles Dodgers in 1986.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] The last pitcher to throw 25 complete games in a season was Rick Langford, who had 28 for the Oakland Athletics in 1980.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] The last pitcher to throw 30 complete games in a season was Catfish Hunter, who did so for the New York Yankees in 1975.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] All pitchers above are right-handed, except for Eddie Plank.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] All also played most or all of their careers before the start of the modern live-ball era of baseball, which began during the 1920 season and was fully established in 1921.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] Among pitchers whose entire careers were in the live-ball era, the all-time leader in complete games is Warren Spahn, whose total of 382 places him 21st all-time.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] All pitchers were right-handed except Matt Kilroy and Toad Ramsey.
[src:complete-game/complete-game] The record for complete games in a live-ball season is 36, set by Bob Feller in 1946.
